						<h3 class='content_title'>Toronto Transit Speeds</h3>

						<div class='content_body'>
						
							<div class='col1'>

								<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/indexity/6686861143/" title="TTC Speeds 2 by indexity, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7011/6686861143_b0d6623f69_b.jpg" alt="TTC Speeds 2"></a>
								<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/indexity/6722822427/" title="TTC Speeds - Low Sample Rate by indexity, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7169/6722822427_8dddc8e7d3_b.jpg" alt="TTC Speeds - Low Sample Rate"></a>

							</div>
							<div class="col2">

								<p>A data exploration project visualizing the speed of every surface route of the TTC. All the TTC buses and streetcars traced for 6 hours the morning of January 6th, 2012.  Average speed is indicated by colour, red being the slowest, followed by orange, yellow, green and blue.
									</p>	
									
										<p>Check out the feature in <a href="http://torontoist.com/2012/01/colour-coding-your-commute/">Torontoist</a>, as well as some mentions in the
											<a href="http://www.thestar.com/news/transportation/article/1121806--ttc-routes-during-rush-hour-watch-them-all-at-once">Toronto Star</a> and
											<a href="http://www.globaltoronto.com/video/a+birdseye+view+of+the+ttc/video.html?v=2190485386#segments/video">Global News</a>.
											</p>
											
											<p>Thanks to Open Data Toronto.  Build using Processing, QGIS, and some Photoshop for touchups.</p>

							</div>
							
